Evacuate Immediately
 
 
Issued For: Warrnambool
Earthquake Origin: Warrnambool
Incident Name:  
Issued: 29/10/15 9:57 AM

This Advice message is being issued by Geoscience Australia for Warrnambool.
 
Magnitude: 9.5.
 
Everybody evacuate immediately!!
 
 will be visible from nearby communities and roads for the next 24 hours.
 
The next update is expected by 30/10/15 10:00 AM or as the situation changes.
 
Safety Information:
  • Review your bushfire survival plan.
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
  • If you have time check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions.
  • If you are experiencing smoke exposure, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.

 

Stay Informed:

  • Via www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • Tune to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Call the Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667.
  • Deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the FireReady App or follow CFA_Updates on Twitter (#VicFires) or Facebook.
  • Road closures: check VicRoads website.

Community Update

 
DELWP - WYE RIVER - JAMIESON TRACK - 1552223
ISSUED: 26/01/16 3:50 PM

This update is being issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning for Wye River and Separation Creek Communities. 

Community members and tourists are advised that there is a severe thunderstorm warning for tomorrow.
 
For your safety escort visits for residents of Wye River and Separation Creek will be suspended for tomorrow Wednesday 27th January until further notice.
 
The Great Ocean Road will remain open and road users are asked to take extreme care while travelling and do NOT drive through any flood water.
 

Incident Information:
Possible Thunderstorm and Flood Activity due to potential severe weather conditions

During heavy rain, runoff may cause flash flooding. Flash floods are fast flowing and can carry dangerous debris including boulders, branches and trees, especially after fires when this debris can be easily dislodged.

Trees that have been burnt or damaged by heat and fire can become unstable and are more prone to falling in windy or wet conditions.

Flash floods after fires are more likely to cause erosion of river beds and banks due to an increase of debris. Flash flooding is also more likely to damage or wash away roads and bridges after fires because of the debris.

The lack of vegetation on the ground, and the potential change in soil properties, can increase the runoff of water during rainfall, changing how floods behave.

Rocks and soil are more easily dislodged, with the potential to trigger a landslide in wet conditions.

Water Contamination:
Due to potential heavy rain fall after fires, floods can bring a greater amount of soil, debris and ash to local waterways.

Soil, trees and rocks blocking waterways and causing erosion. In some
cases, blocked waterways can change the expected flow of floodwater.
 
Air Quality:
The EPA currently has no reports of effected air quality in and around the Wye River and Separation Creek areas. Please refer to the EPA website for further information.

Flash Flooding:
The potential for flash flooding happens quickly. There may be little or no 
warning. The arrival time or depth of a flash flood can usually not be predicted.
Remember, you may not receive any official warning.
Never wait for a warning to act.

Land Slips:
Landslips can occur after fires followed by periods of heavy rain, when the ground is soft and at its heaviest, causing a slope to collapse. Land slippage can result in significant damage to buildings and infrastructure and is a risk to life, both on and below the landslip area. 
The loss of forest 
cover due to fire has a destabilising effect on the soil, when extensive root systems that bind the soil have largely gone
and excess water formerly used by trees now remains in the soil.

Staying Safe:
Avoid walking in burnt areas or along stream banks during or directly after heavy rainfall due to the risk of flash flooding.

Do not drive in adverse conditions such as storms and heavy rain. Follow any cautionary road signs including detours.

Never drive, ride, swim or walk through floodwater.

Floodwater can be deep and damage roads and bridges especially after fires.

Key Contacts:
  • There may still road closures in the area - check www.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Bureau of Meteorology website at www.bom.vic.gov.au
  • ses.vic.gov.au/floodsafe
  • Triple Zero (000) for a life threatening emergency.
  • Colac Otway Shire www.colacotway.vic.gov.au
  • Environment Protection Authority. www.epa.vic.gov.au
 

Health & Wellbeing Information:
  • For information regarding Bushfires and your health visit www.health.vic.gov.au/environment/bushfires.htm
  • Anyone with concerns about their health should seek medical advice or call NURSE-ON-CALL on 1300 60 60 24.

Useful Information:
  • Via www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • Call the Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667.

Counselling & Support Services:

  • Lifeline www.lifeline.org.au phone: 13 11 14
  • Beyond Blue www.beyondblue.org.au     phone 1300 224 636
  • Kids Helpline www.kidshelp.com.au       phone 1800 551 800
  • SANE Australia www.sane.org                  phone 1800 187 263

Stay Informed:
  • Tune to ABC Local radio and commercial radio stations.
  • Deaf, hard of hearing or if you have a speech/communication impairment you can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English. call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL.  If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.

Advice - All Clear
 
 
 
Issued For: Braybrook, Brooklyn, Sunshine, Sunshine West, Tottenham
Incident Location: BROOKLYN
Incident Name: BUNTING RD 
Issued: 27/01/16 7:44 AM
 
 
This is an All Clear message being issued by Metropolitan Fire Brigade for Braybrook, Brooklyn, Sunshine, Sunshine West, Tottenham.
 
The rubbish fire at Bunting Avenue BROOKLYN is now safe.
 
Bunting Avenue is now open.  Traffic in the area may still be affected as the MFB is still present.
 
People located within the area are now able to resume normal activities Please open windows and doors to ventilate your home or business.
 
This will be the final message for this incident.

Advice
 
 
Issued For: Wye River, Separation Creek, Kennett River, Grey River, Sugarloaf, Allenvale, Lorne, Wongarra
Fire Origin: Wye River, Jamieson Track
Incident Name: DELWP - WYE RIVER - JAMIESON TRACK - 1552223 
Issued: 27/01/16 10:05 AM

This Advice message is being issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning for Wye River, Separation Creek, Kennett River, Grey River, Sugarloaf, Allenvale, Lorne, Wongarra.

The fire is now contained.

The Great Ocean Road remains open. Motorists need to take note and adhere to all traffic signs in the area.

Road closures and no entry signs around the fire effected areas remain in place. Walking tracks leading into fire effected areas have also been closed. NO public access to these areas are permitted, with road closures reviewed daily and may be in place for some time that may impact on public access at:
  • Jamieson Track, Separation Creek
  • Sarsfield Street, Separation Creek
  • Stanway Drive, Separation Creek
  • Olive Street, Separation Creek
  • The Boulevarde, Wye River
  • Bird Track, Wye River
  • Wallace Avenue, Wye River
Firefighting resources will remain in place to extinguish any hot spots and to secure the fire perimeter.

People should not be complacent, but remain vigilant whilst there is fire activity in the area.
 
There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.

Wildlife response arrangements

The Department of Environment, Land, Water and Planning (DELWP) has ongoing measures in place to enable the rescue, treatmentand rehabilitation of wildlife affected by fire.

The Triage Centre at Lorne is closed.     

To report injured wildlife outside the fire ground area contact Wildlife Victoria on 1300 094 535 or help for Wildlif on 0417 380 687

To report injured wildlife inside the fireground north of Kennett River and south of Cumberland River contact DELWP on 5233 5565

The fire ground remains closed to the public

 
The next update is expected by 28/01/16 10:30 AM or as the situation changes.
 
Safety Information:
  • Review your bushfire survival plan.
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
  • If you have time check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions.
  • If you are experiencing smoke exposure, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.
  • Smoke Information:
  • The EPA currently has no reports of effected air quality in and around the Wye River and Separation Creek areas. Please refer to the EPA website for further information.
  • Smoke can affect people's health.
  • People with heart or lung conditions (including asthma), children, pregnant woman and older people are more sensitive to the effects of breathing smoke.
  • People with existing heart or lung conditions (including asthma) should follow the treatment plan advised by their doctor.
  • If you are experiencing any symptoms that may be due to smoke exposure, seek medical advice or call NURSE-ON-CALL on 1300 60 60 24.
  • Anyone experiencing wheezing, chest tightness and difficulty breathing should call 000.

 Stay Informed:

  • Visit the Community Recovery Information centre at the Colac Otway Shire Office, 69 Nelson Street, Apollo Bay. Open 10am - 4pm daily.
  • Call the Colac Otway Shire Bushfire Information Call Centre on 03 5232 9400 and select option 1. Open 8:30am - 5pm weekdays and 10am - 4pm weekends.
  • Visit the Lorne Bushfire Information Centre, shop 9 Cumberland Complex, Mountjoy Parade, Lorne. Open daily 10am - 4pm.
  • Via www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • Tune to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Call the Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667.
  • Deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the FireReady App or follow Vic Emergency on Twitter (#VicFires) or Facebook.
  • Road closures: check VicRoads website.
  • Environment Protection Authority www.epa.vic.gov.au
